{"id":"1110.4823","submitter":"Zsolt Langi Dr.","authors":"Zsolt L\\'angi and M\\'arton Nasz\\'odi and Istv\\'an Talata","title":"Ball and Spindle Convexity with respect to a Convex Body","comments":"27 pages, 5 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1007/s00010-012-0160-z","report-no":null,"categories":"math.MG math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Let $C\\subset {\\mathbb R}^n$ be a convex body. We introduce two notions of\nconvexity associated to C. A set $K$ is $C$-ball convex if it is the\nintersection of translates of $C$, or it is either $\\emptyset$, or ${\\mathbb\nR}^n$. The $C$-ball convex hull of two points is called a $C$-spindle. $K$ is\n$C$-spindle convex if it contains the $C$-spindle of any pair of its points. We\ninvestigate how some fundamental properties of conventional convex sets can be\nadapted to $C$-spindle convex and $C$-ball convex sets. We study separation\nproperties and Carath\\'eodory numbers of these two convexity structures. We\ninvestigate the basic properties of arc-distance, a quantity defined by a\ncentrally symmetric planar disc $C$, which is the length of an arc of a\ntranslate of $C$, measured in the $C$-norm, that connects two points. Then we\ncharacterize those $n$-dimensional convex bodies $C$ for which every $C$-ball\nconvex set is the $C$-ball convex hull of finitely many points. Finally, we\nobtain a stability result concerning covering numbers of some $C$-ball convex\nsets, and diametrically maximal sets in $n$-dimensional Minkowski spaces.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 21 Oct 2011 15:24:47 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 23 Jul 2012 05:32:20 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 5 Sep 2012 13:33:44 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-09-06"}
{"id":"1110.4824","submitter":"Dmitrii V. Pasechnik","authors":"Etienne de Klerk, Dmitrii V. Pasechnik","title":"Improved lower bounds for the 2-page crossing numbers of K_{m,n} and K_n\n  via semidefinite programming","comments":"20 pages (ignore pages 21 and 22 produced by the arxive.org script,\n  with copies of pictures inserted elsewhere in the text)","journal-ref":"SIAM J. Optim. 22-2 (2012), pp. 581-595","doi":"10.1137/110852206","report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO math.OC","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  It has been long conjectured that the crossing numbers of the complete\nbipartite graph K_{m,n} and of the complete graph K_n equal Z(m,n) (the value\nconjectured by Zarankiewicz, who came up with a drawing reaching this value)\nand Z(n) :=Z(n,n-2)/4, respectively.\n  In a 2-page drawing of a graph, the vertices are drawn on a straight line\n(the spine), and each edge is contained in one of the half-planes of the spine.\nThe 2-page crossing number v_2(G) of a graph G is the minimum number of\ncrossings in a 2-page drawing of G. Somewhat surprisingly, there are 2-page\ndrawings of K_{m,n} (respectively, K_n) with exactly Z(m, n) (respectively,\nZ(n)) crossings, thus yielding the conjectures (I) v_2(Km,n) =Z(m,n), and (II)\nv_2(Kn) = Z(n).\n  It is known that (I) holds for min{m, n} <=6, and that (II) holds for n<=14.\nIn this paper we prove that (I) holds asymptotically (that is, lim_n v_2\n(K_{m,n})/Z (m, n) = 1) for m=7 and 8.\n  We also prove (II) for 15<=n<=18 and n=20,24, and establish the asymptotic\nestimate lim_n v_2(K_n)/Z(n) >= 0.9253.\n  The previous best-known lower bound involved the constant 0.8594.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 21 Oct 2011 15:27:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-07-25"}
